","justification":"This depends on real git behavior for unborn HEAD/no-commit repos (often non-zero exits/messages) and CLI error-handling around subprocess calls. In-process mocks can miss exact failure mode. No AI/ML dependency.","test_description":"Initialize an empty git repo with no commits, invoke the CLI subprocess against it, and assert successful execution with an empty/zeroed structured report to stdout.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is end-to-end correctness against real repository history semantics (rename/add/delete/modify across commits). Real git history construction and subprocess invocation are part of the failure boundary; stubs can drift from git’s actual behavior and hide defects.","test_description":"Programmatically build a temporary repo with a known sequence of commits containing adds, deletes, renames, and modifications; run CLI subprocess; assert reported counts exactly match the constructed history.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Correctness depends on real git index vs working-tree states and how CLI queries them via subprocess. This boundary is OS/filesystem + real git semantics; mocking can hide discrepancies between staged/unstaged handling.","test_description":"In a real temp repo, create identical file edits in two scenarios (staged and unstaged), run CLI subprocess for each scenario, and assert stdout structured reports are byte-for-byte equal (or semantically equal after st